Arduino Sample Code (Obstacle Detection + Motor Control)

// Pins for Ultrasonic Sensor

const int trigPin = 9;

const int echoPin = 10;

// Pins for Motor Driver

const int motor1Pin1 = 4; 

const int motor1Pin2 = 5; 

const int motor2Pin1 = 6;

const int motor2Pin2 = 7;

void setup() {

  Serial.begin(9600);

  pinMode(trigPin, OUTPUT);

  pinMode(echoPin, INPUT);

  pinMode(motor1Pin1, OUTPUT);

  pinMode(motor1Pin2, OUTPUT);

  pinMode(motor2Pin1, OUTPUT);

  pinMode(motor2Pin2, OUTPUT);

}

void loop() {

  long duration;

  int distance;

  // Ultrasonic sensor reading

  digitalWrite(trigPin, LOW);

  delayMicroseconds(2);

  digitalWrite(trigPin, HIGH);

  delayMicroseconds(10);

  digitalWrite(trigPin, LOW);

  duration = pulseIn(echoPin, HIGH);

  distance = duration * 0.034 / 2; // Convert to cm

  Serial.println(distance);

  if (distance < 15) { // Obstacle detected within 15cm

    stopMotors();

    delay(500);

    turnRight();  // Turn to avoid obstacle

    delay(600);

  } else {

    moveForward();

  }

  delay(100);

}

void moveForward() {

  digitalWrite(motor1Pin1, HIGH);

  digitalWrite(motor1Pin2, LOW);

  digitalWrite(motor2Pin1, HIGH);

  digitalWrite(motor2Pin2, LOW);

}

void stopMotors() {

  digitalWrite(motor1Pin1, LOW);

  digitalWrite(motor1Pin2, LOW);

  digitalWrite(motor2Pin1, LOW);

  digitalWrite(motor2Pin2, LOW);

}

void turnRight() {

  digitalWrite(motor1Pin1, LOW);

  digitalWrite(motor1Pin2, HIGH);

  digitalWrite(motor2Pin1, HIGH);

  digitalWrite(motor2Pin2, LOW);

}

# **Basic Fritzing Diagram (Wiring Sketch)**

Arduino to Ultrasonic to Motor Driver to Motors

Ultrasonic Sensor → Arduino Pins 9 & 10

Arduino → Motor Driver Inputs

Motor Driver Outputs → Left & Right Motors

Battery connected to Motor Driver (12V)

Arduino powered by USB/Separate Battery (5V)

a simple and clean Wiring Diagram for your Mars Rover using Arduino, Ultrasonic sensor, Motor Driver (L298N or L293D), and DC Motors.

# **Wiring Overview (Text version first)**

| **Component** | **Arduino Pin** | **Note** |
| --- | --- | --- |
| Ultrasonic Sensor Trigger | 9 | Digital Output |
| Ultrasonic Sensor Echo | 10 | Digital Input |
| Motor Driver IN1 | 4 | Digital Output |
| Motor Driver IN2 | 5 | Digital Output |
| Motor Driver IN3 | 6 | Digital Output |
| Motor Driver IN4 | 7 | Digital Output |
| Motor Driver Power (VCC) | 12V Battery | External battery needed |
| Arduino Power | USB or 5V battery | Separate if needed |
| Motor Outputs (M1, M2) | Connected to Wheels | DC Motors |

Fritzing Style Wiring Sketch (Simple Version):

          +--------------------------------+

          |           Arduino UNO          |

          |                                |

Trig Pin--|9                             5V|---> Ultrasonic Sensor VCC

Echo Pin--|10                            GND|---> Ultrasonic Sensor GND

IN1 ------|4                               

IN2 ------|5                               

IN3 ------|6                               

IN4 ------|7                               

          +--------------------------------+

            +-------------------------+

            | Motor Driver (L298N)      |

            | (or L293D)                |

            +-------------------------+

          IN1, IN2, IN3, IN4 from Arduino

          Motor Outputs to Wheels

          VCC (12V Battery)

          GND connected to Arduino GND

     [Ultrasonic Sensor]

        - VCC: 5V

        - GND: GND

        - Trigger: Pin 9

        - Echo: Pin 10

**Quick Notes:**

- **Common GND** between Arduino and Motor Driver.

- **12V Battery** powers motors separately because Arduino 5V can't drive motors directly.

- **Arduino can be USB-powered** during demo, or by a small 5V portable battery.

- **Ultrasonic Sensor reads distance** -> Arduino decides -> Moves or Turns motors accordingly.